    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-05-26T07:30:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-05-26T07:30:00-05:00" n="246"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d246">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">845.00/1962: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Officer in Charge at New Delhi</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Merrell</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">New Delhi</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-05-26T19:00:00+06:30"
                            >May 26, 1943—7 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 9:52 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>366. Reference my No. 365, May 26, 6 p.m. It is presumed that Gandhi’s letter was
                    a response to Jinnah’s statement. The communiqué appears to be an additional
                    indication that the Government of India does not desire a solution of the
                        deadlock.<note n="49" xml:id="d246fn49">On May 27 the Adviser on Political
                        Relations (Murray) forwarded this telegram to Under Secretary of State
                        Welles and to the Secretary of State with the comment: “As you will note,
                        the attached telegram, which has just come in from New Delhi, confirms the
                        views which I expressed to you in a memorandum sent to you early this
                        morning [not found in Department files] to the effect that the present
                        attitude of the Government of India is to prevent rather than effect a
                        solution of the political deadlock in India.”</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Merrell</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
